related_questions.question: Why is a hamburger called hamburger?
related_questions.snippet: After running out of their hot pork sandwiches at the Erie County Fair in Hamburg, NY, Frank and Charles Menches mixed ground beef with spices and sold it between bread, naming it “the hamburger” after the city where the fair was held.

related_questions.question: Is hamburger and burger same?
related_questions.snippet: Well, the term "burger" is a more general term that refers to any sandwich made with a patty of ground meat. Burgers can be made with beef, chicken, pork, turkey, or even vegetables. On the other hand, a hamburger specifically refers to a sandwich made with a beef patty.

buttons.subtitle: What Is Hamburger Made Of
buttons.title: What is a Burger Made Of? - WebMD
buttons.snippet: A burger is a patty of ground beef grilled and placed between two halves of a bun. Slices of raw onion, lettuce, bacon, mayonnaise, and other ingredients add flavor. Burgers are considered an American food but are popular around the world. In Japan, teriyaki burgers are popular.

buttons.subtitle: Is Hamburger Beef Or Pork?
buttons.title: Can hamburger meat contain other ingredients? - Ask USDA
buttons.snippet: If labeled as a "Hamburger," it can contain all beef or beef and beef fat. Other permitted ingredients include dry seasonings like spices and flavorings. Water (and other liquids) and fillers (like breadcrumbs and flours) are not permitted.
snippet_highlighted_words: it can contain all beef or beef and beef fat

buttons.subtitle: What Temperature To Cook Hamburgers In The Oven
buttons.title: Burger Temperature Chart - WebstaurantStore
buttons.snippet: Hamburger Internal Temperature The USDA marks the minimum safe temperature for ground beef as 160 degrees Fahrenheit, although not all burgers are cooked to this temperature. Depending on how you're preparing your burger, the meat's internal temperature may not reach 160 degrees Fahrenheit.
